        jTextArea1.setText("\nWorld War I ‚Äì Grade 8 IEB History Notes\n\nüìÖ WHEN DID WWI HAPPEN?\n- Start: 28 July 1914\n- End: 11 November 1918\n- Lasted for over 4 years\n\nüåç MAIN CAUSES OF WWI ‚Äì (M.A.I.N)\n\n1. MILITARISM\n- Countries wanted strong armies and navies to protect themselves.\n- Germany and Britain competed to have the best navy.\n- More weapons meant countries were ready for war at any time.\n\n2. ALLIANCES\n- Countries made agreements to support each other if attacked.\n- Triple Alliance: Germany, Austria-Hungary, Italy\n- Triple Entente: Britain, France, Russia\n- Alliances caused a small conflict to become a world war.\n\n3. IMPERIALISM\n- European countries took over parts of Africa, Asia, and the Middle East.\n- Fights over land created anger and mistrust between nations.\n- Germany wanted more colonies like Britain and France had.\n\n4. NATIONALISM\n- People were extremely proud of their country.\n- Some ethnic groups (like Serbs and Slavs) wanted independence from empires.\n- This created tension inside countries like Austria-Hungary.\n\nüí• THE SPARK ‚Äì THE ASSASSINATION\n- Archduke Franz Ferdinand (heir to Austria-Hungary) was killed in Sarajevo on 28 June 1914.\n- He was shot by Gavrilo Princip, a member of a Serbian nationalist group.\n- Austria-Hungary blamed Serbia and declared war, starting a chain reaction.\n\nüåê COUNTRIES INVOLVED\n\nALLIED POWERS (Entente):\n- Britain, France, Russia, later joined by Italy (1915), USA (1917), and others\n\nCENTRAL POWERS:\n- Germany, Austria-Hungary, Ottoman Empire, Bulgaria\n\nü™ñ TRENCH WARFARE\n- Fought mainly on the Western Front (France and Belgium).\n- Long ditches dug to protect soldiers.\n- Life in the trenches was hard: cold, wet, full of rats and diseases.\n- Soldiers suffered from shell shock (PTSD).\n\nüí£ NEW WEAPONS AND TECHNOLOGY\n- Machine guns: caused mass deaths\n- Artillery: large cannons used to bomb enemies\n- Poison gas: caused blindness, burns, and death (e.g., mustard gas)\n- Tanks: first used in WWI to cross difficult land\n- Submarines (U-boats): used by Germany to attack ships\n- Airplanes: used for spying and dropping bombs\n\nüåç WAR OUTSIDE EUROPE\n- Fought in Africa, Asia, and the Middle East.\n- European colonies (like South Africa and India) helped their empires.\n- Many African soldiers were forced or recruited to fight.\n\nüáøüá¶ SOUTH AFRICA IN WWI\n- South Africa was part of the British Empire.\n- Prime Minister Louis Botha supported Britain and sent troops.\n- South African soldiers fought in:\n  - German South-West Africa (now Namibia)\n  - East Africa\n  - Europe (Western Front)\n- Some Afrikaners (like those in the 1914 Rebellion) opposed fighting for Britain.\n\nüá∫üá∏ THE USA JOINS\n- The USA joined in 1917 after German submarines attacked American ships.\n- Helped the Allies win the war.\n\nüïäÔ∏è END OF THE WAR\n- Germany became weaker and people were starving.\n- Armistice signed on 11 November 1918 ‚Äì war officially ended.\n\nüìú TREATY OF VERSAILLES (1919)\n- Germany was blamed for the war.\n- Had to pay reparations (money) to other countries.\n- Lost land and had to reduce its army.\n- Many Germans were angry about the treaty.\n\nüß† IMPACT OF WWI\n- Over 16 million people died.\n- Empires like Germany, Austria-Hungary, Russia, and Ottoman Empire collapsed.\n- The war led to big political and social changes.\n- Set the stage for World War II.\n");
